<div id="review_2102374048" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2102374048" />
    <a title="Lida" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5471730-lida"><img alt="Lida" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1339546814p2/5471730.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2102374048?book_show_action=true">Sep 01, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lida" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lida" href="/user/show/5471730-lida">Lida</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2102374048" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10930100039690051359">Sometimes I am tempted to change the rating of a book when there is a satisfying ending. While this book ends happily, there are many parts of the story that are far-fetched. Who gets on a plane to Seoul with a handbag and some toiletries with 45 minutes to spare? Who would continue to conceal their professional identity even when they have fallen in love? What friend would set up a dating profile for another and set them up on a blind date under the pretense of a business meeting? <br/><br/>The author, M</span>
  <span id="freeText10930100039690051359" style="display:none">Sometimes I am tempted to change the rating of a book when there is a satisfying ending. While this book ends happily, there are many parts of the story that are far-fetched. Who gets on a plane to Seoul with a handbag and some toiletries with 45 minutes to spare? Who would continue to conceal their professional identity even when they have fallen in love? What friend would set up a dating profile for another and set them up on a blind date under the pretense of a business meeting? <br /><br />The author, Marc Levy, is purportedly France's best-selling author, but the writing is terrible. (This proves my point that best sellers don't have to be good, just sell a lot.) Rarely are his characters honest with themselves or others. Levy's main characters mutter their real observations and feelings under their breath and then say the opposite, or worse: "Nothing!" Come on. Some of the tricks played on friends are mean and belie the term friend. I will not even comment on the professional dilemma faced by the main character, Paul, except to say again, far-fetched. The theme of this book is running: away from success, commitment, love, friendship, you name it. My advice is to do the same.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10930100039690051359" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


