    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2739188018" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2739188018" />
    <a title="Ceecee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/60964126-ceecee"><img alt="Ceecee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1571497768p2/60964126.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2739188018?book_show_action=true">May 21, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ceecee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ceecee" href="/user/show/60964126-ceecee">Ceecee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/35131649-p-s-from-paris">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2739188018" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6877228248911474714">Well, I was in the market for something a bit lighter than my usual genre and Marc Levy did not let me down. I’ve read 3 of his books so far and liked all of them. This was charming, funny with two good twists and with likeable characters. What’s not to love? The translation was good as far as we know 🤣(joke. You’ll have to read the book to understand. But seriously it was good). The main characters were Mia a British actress and Paul, an American writer from SF but relocated to Paris. Mia was m</span>
  <span id="freeText6877228248911474714" style="display:none">Well, I was in the market for something a bit lighter than my usual genre and Marc Levy did not let me down. I’ve read 3 of his books so far and liked all of them. This was charming, funny with two good twists and with likeable characters. What’s not to love? The translation was good as far as we know 🤣(joke. You’ll have to read the book to understand. But seriously it was good). The main characters were Mia a British actress and Paul, an American writer from SF but relocated to Paris. Mia was married to David who was a cheater so understandably the marriage had hit the rocks. Paul was in love with the Korean translator of his book Kyong where his books were very popular. <br /><br />There were some lovely touching moments in the book such as Mia suffering from insomnia rested her head on the shoulder of a caricaturist in Place du Tetre. He was a peripheral character but really interesting. All the characters were lovely (except David natch) and the settings - well let’s face it you can’t go wrong with SF and Paris can you? Part of the story where the first twist happens was in Seoul and that sounded fascinating and I liked the sections about N Korea too, which made the book relevant and topical. I loved that Paul and Mia pretended to each other and their muttered private thoughts were often very funny. I loved the twist on the twist with Paul’s award winning latest book and the ending was exactly what I’d hoped for. </span>
  <a data-text-id="6877228248911474714" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

